segments.text: Right on the truck, you know, back and forth from the stable hauling the hay and what not.
That was, I enjoyed that.
But those Army people took care of it.
At that time,
and the artillery, they had the caissons, I think it was, or two-wheel things, and the horses would pull that.
And that was quite an occasion, because all that was done out on the drill field.
for review or whatnot.
But those Army people took care of the horses, and I suppose I remember how they used to saddle-soap the saddles and do that sort of work.
Describe the student body generally.
Where did they come from?
What kind of families?
What were their attitudes?
What were Aggies like in the 30s?
Well, these were all, you might say, pretty well just country boys, of course.
They weren't over what?
I don't remember the exact figures.
They weren't over two or three thousand, were they?
At that time, it might have been five or two or three thousand.
You got to where you knew everybody.
First name and last name, of course.
Kind of knew where they were from.
You know in these bull sessions where you'd sit there and talk to each other.
I've forgotten a lot of it.
Were they liberal, conservative?
What was their attitude about hard work?
About hard work?
Well, I think everyone liked
appreciated it.
They appreciated everything that we had and were thankful of it.
I know some of these boys that came down, particularly in the project houses, they were just thankful that they could go to college
and be able to afford it.
And were most of them from the country in small towns or were there a lot of city boys from Houston and Dallas?
I would say at that time I thought they were mostly from out in the small towns.
The 4-H at that time, or extension service, we got a lot of our people that came, at that time they had a

A group that came in once a year, I can't remember exactly, Extension Service of the 4-H, and I suppose at that time, I don't know how many thousand kids and their teachers would come to A&M, and they had a big tent for soda water and whatnot out on the drill field, and they stayed in the dormitories.
And they brought in every kid that wanted to come.
Later years, as I understand, they started restricting it to winners or certain ones.
But at that time, every kid that wanted to come down there got to come.
And they would come by every means from every little small town in Texas.
And I remember when I was going to school,
I went around and I wasn't supposed to.
College still had restrictions, but when I was going to grade school, I got some postcards from a place in Brown, and I sold those postcards on the campus.
They were postcards of A&M and things like that, and I believe I made as much as $25 or $30 in a day.
I really, that really helped me.
Those kids bought those postcards, and I even was able to get them some stamps along once in a while.
And I, this place in Bryan called Haswell's, up in, they had little postcards, I don't know how many years, and I almost got them all.
Where did those kids stay on the campus?
Where did they sleep?
They stayed in the dormitory.
And it seemed like to me some of them might have stayed in tents or something.
I don't know.
Oh, there must have been at that time maybe 10,000 or 12,000, best I remember.
They really went all out for it.
Did they use DeWare Fieldhouse?
Did they sleep there?
I just don't remember.
I don't remember that.
All right, back to the student body.
Do you remember a variety of students, German, Italian, Mexican, in terms of their ancestry?
Were there some German-American boys?
If they were, I didn't realize it.
Well, I'm talking about, say, from Brenham.
Like the kids from Brenham, were there some Czech and German?
We weren't conscious of that at the time.
All right.
As a matter of fact, way back there, you might have this hard to believe, when I lived across from my grandfather and going to grade school,
I didn't realize the blacks were going to another school.
It didn't enter my mind.
I played with them after, in the cotton field after I got out of class, stuff like that.
But it didn't enter my mind that they were going to another school.
And there was a black elementary school in College Station then, I presume.
I don't know where it was.
I don't know.
Where you said out in the cotton field, where was that?
Well, that's back where the campus theater was.
Oh, okay.
That's where the campus theater is now.
That was plowed ground?
There was some fields there?
There was a cotton pasture there, and part of a pen there that my grandfather kept cattle.
He had been on the board of directors at A&M, and he sold cattle to the mess hall at A&M.
Also, our water, we had a little problem with getting water from A&M.
At one time, they didn't want to give us water over there.
Of course, my grandfather had a well in the back of the house, and then I suppose they got other water at A&M.
Later, I think we got some water coming from A&M.
And what was his name, your grandfather?
W.C. Boyette.
He was on the board of directors at Texas A&M, as I understand, one time.
And they also had that store at the North Gate that he operated.
When did your grandfather come to Brazos County?
Do you know?
No.
Did he grow up?
No, I don't really.
My mother was born there.
My mother went to Villa Maria Academy.
Matter of fact, I've got a picture in there that shows her on the basketball team.
Somehow or another, my mother lived at College Station, but she went to Villa Maria.
Because that was out east edge of Bryan, wasn't it?
Yeah.
I don't know how she got there.
By buggy, I suppose.
You mentioned the Interurban.
When did it quit running, do you know?
Was it operating when you were an A&M student?
I'm quite sure it was, because I remember we went to, the student was, I was still going to Bryan once in a while to the picture show, and it came down right
in front of where the campus theater is, and I believe that's where they had a house where they sold tickets or whatnot, and that was close to what's called a bachelor's hall.
There used to be a bachelor's hall at A&M.
But bachelor's hall, they served meals in there and everything.
I think that was kind of
professors that were not married that still wanted, could live on the campus.
Most of all of those that lived on the campus were professors or workers at A&M like the power plant, plumbers, like they had a house also at A&M.
Now the interurban, where did the tracks run between College Station and Bryan?
The Interurban first started over here where the old Eagle office was, and I think I'd say it went down Texas Avenue and turned on... College?
Turned on Cabot.
Cabot.
There used to be a big house up there, Cabot.
It went on down, and you know how it crosses
North Avenue, turns around through there, and then it, that's why that street cuts out through there.
Then it went across, what is it, College Avenue, and circled all around
There used to be a creek over there, I believe.
And it turned, then turned to the left and came down to the, in front of the, where the campus theater is.
And there was a building there and that's where it stopped.
It didn't go, it stopped just at the edge of campus.
It didn't go right on the edge on the campus.
About how often did it run?
Every hour?
About every hour.
And I think it was two of them.
And they would alternate, and sometimes it was real difficult to get on there, particularly you came to Brown on the weekend and went to the picture show.
Did any of your buddies have cars?
Any of your student buddies?
Not that I remember.
We used to train all the time.
They used to train to go anywhere.
The train was the transportation.
How often did you ride the train while you were a student?
Well, I went to Dallas, I remember.
I went to Louisiana that one time.
I think it was Baton Rouge.
I think for the Rice game I hitchhiked.
I know I went to Dallas.
There might have been one or two other trips.
Oh, I went on the train to the Baylor game.
I remember that.
But the other trips I don't really remember.
Do you remember some students who had to drop out because they didn't have the money?
No, I really don't.
Once you registered there, it seemed like, you know, they were like the project house boys.
They required, at that time, when you registered at A&M, if you were on campus, you had to pay for the room and the board.
The whole semester.
So if you registered, you were for the semester.
Now, the project house boys didn't have to pay that, of course, and they mainly ate food that was brought from their home county.
Describe the variety of jobs that students had on campus.
Y'all mowed the lawn and cleaned up the horse stables.
What else?
Well, I remember a lot of students were lucky enough to be waiters in the mess hall.
O.D.
Butler was one of them, and he learned a lot about
things as a waiter.
Did you know O.D.
as a student?
No, I didn't.
Knew him later in the reserve.
There weren't many other jobs that I could really... Did they do janitor work?
Did they sweep floors?
I believe they did.
Well, I don't remember any cleaning crew that would have been there.
What were the best student jobs?
If you had your choice.
The mess hall.
Is that right?
I think, for what I remember.
Who ran the mess hall then?
Who was in charge of the food service?
Well, I believe it was a man named Duncan.
And he had a daughter that also went to school at Consolidated.
He was in charge of the mess hall, and he had a house that was there near the mess hall.
They had a real two-story house, and that's where the board of directors stayed and where they did a little high-type entertaining, as I remember, there in his home.
And the board of directors stayed there.
Now, you did eat some on the campus, didn't you?
Yes.
Describe the food that was served in the dining halls.
Well, it was very good.
Maybe I ate there one term, I'm not sure.
I didn't eat a whole lot at times at the mess hall.
But you had to march in, of course, and sit down, take your hat off, and you had to know the names for everything on there or you didn't get it.
What were some of those names?
I can't remember now.
But you had, everything had a certain name.
And you had to know that.
They didn't rush you.
You were able to sit down and enjoy your meal.
It wasn't like some of I've heard some places since then.
It wasn't that way.
You could, you could, but you did have to know and have, you had to act a certain way.
And of course, you had a certain place to sit too.
That was all really well organized.
The only thing you could do is when you walked into the mess hall, as you got up to the steps, then you could start yelling and running.
But then, when you got in there, then you, that was over.
You acted correctly.
Well, as you recall, what was your favorite dining hall food?
What did you like best?
I can't remember.
I really can't.
Was the food good?
Oh, yes.
Yes.
Was there enough of it?
Oh, yeah.
Oh, yeah.
Had plenty of it.
It was very good.

I remember when I was going to, one thing I can remember about the, mainly about the mess hall, was when I was delivering newspapers as, when I was going to the slaughter days, and I'd take several newspapers and go in the kitchen, and I could have some of the best
Fried ham sandwiches.
I remember that.
Well, those days really, anything you had a lot of times, you appreciated because a lot of times you were hungry.
And when you ate, a lot of times, we were hungry, and of course young people like that eat more anyway.
My mother did real well.
She ran a boarding house there off the campus.
Several others did.
A lot of ladies did.
Now who ate in those boarding houses?
Some professors and some students that were day students.
They called them day students.
And a lot of the
army people.
Those army people that were taking care of that, they ate in boarding houses.
And some of the professors, some of the different ones off the campus.
But I went through a lot of times there.
My mother did real well at feeding me and everything, but way back there I went hungry several times.
I appreciated, when I sit down and I appreciated
I'd go to a friend's house.
I was always welcome.
At that time, you didn't have to call.
As kids, you didn't have to call or anything like that.
You'd go there, and if it was come time to eat, you'd sit down, and they might not have anything but maybe cornbread and a big bowl of stew or something.
But you were always welcome.
Now, you said your mother ran a boarding house where?
Well, my grandfather
had built three houses, I believe it was, right across from where he lived at where the campus theater is.
We lived in the second one.
And that's where the house was located.
That's where the house was located that they stole that house from.
And did some students live in these boarding houses?
Did people live, rent a bedroom?
Yes.
The first house right across from my grandfather was right near what the old Stucco building is.

My uncle built a kind of a rooming house there, and one or two of the, I think, of the single professors had rooms there, and then he rented some rooms to people that maybe worked on the campus, maybe at the exchange store, stuff like that.
And then there was another house down below there that's gone now, a two-story house, and she ran a boarding house there.
She had a few rooms there.
There was no hotel or anything like that around.
Was Lupo yet in business at the Northgate?
No, I think Lupo was going to school when I was.
Okay.
He might have been...
handling books at the time.
I bought my books secondhand.
He may have had some little place where he was selling books.
I had to buy a lot of them at the exchange store, I remember, and they were always higher.
And it was over there on the north side of the campus back north of Sabeasa, the exchange store?
Duncan.
If you go around, I think it's, go on the campus from the north gate.
Yes, sir.
There was a house there Mitchell lived in, I believe, and then Duncan, around the mess hall, in the mess hall, and you go around there across Military Walk and on
left with this grocery store on the right was the exchange store.
Yes, sir.
Yes, sir.
And they also had a telegraph station in there.
Oh, I worked for them a little bit delivering some, delivering telegrams.
They were upstairs.
You worked while you were a student?
Right.
Later on, that was one reason I didn't do very good.
I got a part-time job with the triple agriculture department at night, so that's one reason why I didn't do very well at the time.
You mentioned Pinky Downs.
Was he on the campus when you were a student?
Not that I remember.
I knew him later.
That's what I thought.
If the students were going out, was the rock pit, did they go swimming in the rock pits then when you were a student?
It wasn't the fish tank I believe it was.
Okay.
For some of them fish.
They didn't go out much like that.
Did they go to the river sometime and have a quiet party?
Not that I remember.
Now, how did you guys get dates?
Well, it seemed like at that time we didn't get dates like young people do at that age.
Not like it is today.
Did you take a date to the cotton ball or the ring dance?
Do you remember that?
No, I didn't at that time.
I just didn't have the money as best I remember.
Were there some famous visitors?
Fellas didn't go in for dates at that age like they do now.
That was an occasion for some of those girls from CIA to come down here.
You had to buy her flowers, I suppose, and a few things like that.
While you were a student, were there any famous visitors that came to the campus?
that you remember?
I think it was Roosevelt that came and rode the car around Kyle Field.
I don't know whether I was at A&M then or not.
I've forgotten.
But best I remember, I was down there.
It wasn't a real big occasion to me.
We didn't know too much about politics then, didn't worry too much about it.
All we had was radio.
And do you remember what programs y'all enjoyed most on the radio?
What did you listen to most?
No, I didn't listen to too much.
And you lived off campus all your student years?
Yeah.
I lived off campus all the time.
Sometimes I lived in a house across from where the campus seat is.
My grandfather died and then I moved over there.
My mother also ran a boarding house there and we had some extra rooms there.
But that's where I was living when I graduated from A&M.
Do you remember going to Silver Taps as a student?
No, I really don't, but if they had some, I'm sure I was there.
Did you work on Bonfire?
Did you help gather stuff for Bonfire?
I don't remember, but I'm sure I did.
That would have been part of, as I say, every activity, even though I was what they call a day student.

every activity you had you you willingly you didn't have to but you you did now where was bonfire held on the drill field right on the drill field and what i think i i was here at the time but that boy got killed flying over and he dropped a can of gasoline on it oh describe that well as i remember
some student from Texas University came over in a plane.
And he dropped a can of gasoline, as I understand, I don't remember.
And when he came down and he took off, and the rise of the plane ended
turned over to the right somewhere around about hit the ground about where Olsen Field is and killed him.
That's really all I can think of.
Did he drop the can of gas?
As I remember, he did.
But it didn't?
It didn't do any good.
I don't know.
At that time, also, for the bonfire, they put people around at the entrances to A&M.
See, A&M
There weren't very many entrances.
Well, there's still not.
North Gate, I don't remember whether one was up at the, there was one at the South Gate and one at the West Gate.
I don't remember the one being at the East Gate where you could drive onto campus until later.
But see the, more or less, West Gate where the railroad station was.
And bonfire, what was put into the bonfire?
What did they burn?
Well, that was just sticks and crates and all things of that nature.
And about how long did the students work to gather that stuff?
I don't think they worked there as long as they do today.
And how did that outhouse get stolen from your family?
At night.
It was right at the edge of the campus.
And I don't know whether that's the one they put on top or not.
They might have just used it for the wood.
They went around, took these things from the railroad station,
went all around as much as they could and gathered up, usually it was lumber and I reckon trees that had fell down or something like that.
As I remember, we were not the only people that had their outhouse stolen.
Didn't have to.
We didn't object to it at all.
But now I'm assuming that
In those years, y'all didn't worry about something important being stolen.
You didn't have to lock your car, your house.
We didn't have any locks on our house at all.
Might have been a lock put in there.
I don't know whether it was or not.
You didn't have to worry about anything on or off the campus, either one.
There was not that problem.
Do you remember going to final review and commencement?
Describe those.
Well, I remember going to the commencement just a little bit, but you see, at the time, I had to take military science, and even though up until the time I graduated, I had to wear a uniform.

I didn't take ROTC the final two years because I had dropped out with a hernia, and to get what's called advanced contract, you had to have your grades up okay, and even if you had your grades up, to get the advanced contract was difficult.
They didn't have that many openings.
So, after marching around in the final review, I did it as a freshman and a sophomore.
